---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="fail2zig · security posture"
  description="Threat model, design principles, trusted computing base, and responsible disclosure for fail2zig."
  activeNav="/security"
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:20px">
        <span class="dot"></span>Security posture
      </div>
      <h1>
        This is a security tool. Its own security <span style="color:var(--accent)"
          >is the product.</span
        >
      </h1>
      <p class="lede">
        A root-privileged daemon that parses attacker-controlled input has to be held to a higher
        standard than the services it protects. This page documents what that standard is, what
        we're defending against, and where we're still working.
      </p>
      <div class="meta">
        <span><strong>v0.1.0-preview</strong> &middot; current</span>
        <span>last reviewed &middot; <strong>2026-04-10</strong></span>
        <span>audit &middot; <strong>scheduled pre-1.0</strong></span>
        <span
          >report a vuln &rarr; <strong
            ><a
              href="https://github.com/ul0gic/fail2zig/issues/new?labels=security"
              style="color:var(--accent)"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub Issues</a
            ></strong
          ></span
        >
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="eyebrow"><span class="dot"></span>01 &middot; Design principles</div>
        <div>
          <h2>Six properties we refuse to compromise on.</h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="principles">
        <div class="principle">
          <div class="idx">PR.01</div>
          <h3>No runtime interpreter</h3>
          <p>
            No embedded scripting engine, no dynamic code loading in the core daemon. The binary you
            ship is the complete trusted computing base &mdash; what you audit is what runs.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="principle">
          <div class="idx">PR.02</div>
          <h3>No hidden allocations</h3>
          <p>
            Every allocation is explicit, auditable, and bounded. There is no path in the critical
            loop where attacker input can influence an allocator to grow without limit.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="principle">
          <div class="idx">PR.03</div>
          <h3>Bounds-checked hot paths</h3>
          <p>
            Zig's safety-checked build mode catches buffer overflows, integer overflows, and
            out-of-bounds access. Release builds retain safety checks on log parsing and network
            input.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="principle">
          <div class="idx">PR.04</div>
          <h3>Attacker-input isolation</h3>
          <p>
            Log parsing operates on mmap'd or buffered slices with strict line-length limits.
            Malformed lines are dropped, not parsed further. Parsing runs in bounded time per line.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="principle">
          <div class="idx">PR.05</div>
          <h3>Zero-dependency supply chain</h3>
          <p>
            No third-party Zig packages in the critical path. C interop only for stable, audited
            kernel ABIs &mdash; inotify, netfilter, eBPF, sd_journal. Reproducible builds, signed
            binaries.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="principle">
          <div class="idx">PR.06</div>
          <h3>Minimal privilege</h3>
          <p>
            The daemon drops privileges after binding to required resources. Phase 2 adds a
            privilege-separation architecture where the log watcher and ban executor run as distinct
            processes.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="eyebrow"><span class="dot"></span>02 &middot; Trusted computing base</div>
        <div>
          <h2>What runs as root.</h2>
          <p class="lede" style="margin-top:16px">
            The TCB of a security tool is every line of code in privileged context. Ours is small
            enough to read.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tcb-box">
        <div class="tcb-col us">
          <h4>fail2zig &middot; TCB</h4>
          <div class="count">~12k <span class="unit">lines of Zig</span></div>
          <ul>
            <li>Core daemon + parsers</li>
            <li>C shims to kernel ABIs</li>
            <li>Comptime-generated filters</li>
            <li>No third-party packages</li>
            <li>No interpreter, no VM</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="tcb-col them">
          <h4>Typical Python IPS &middot; TCB</h4>
          <div class="count">~45k <span class="unit">LOC + runtime</span></div>
          <ul>
            <li>CPython interpreter</li>
            <li>Python standard library</li>
            <li>python3-systemd</li>
            <li>python3-pyinotify</li>
            <li>Transitive C deps</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="eyebrow"><span class="dot"></span>03 &middot; Threat model</div>
        <div>
          <h2>What an attacker can try, and what happens when they do.</h2>
          <p class="lede" style="margin-top:16px">
            fail2zig's threat model starts from the assumption that every log line is hostile and
            every remote IP is trying.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <table class="threat-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>ID</th><th>Threat</th><th>Mitigation</th><th>Status</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="tid">T.01</td>
            <td class="threat">Attacker crafts log lines to exploit parser bugs</td>
            <td class="mitig">
              Bounds-checked parsing, strict line-length limits, no runtime regex engine,
              comptime-generated parsers, continuous fuzz testing (AFL++, libFuzzer).
            </td>
            <td class="status"><span class="tag safe">Mitigated</span></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="tid">T.02</td>
            <td class="threat">Attacker floods logs to exhaust daemon memory</td>
            <td class="mitig">
              Fixed-size arena allocator with a hard, configurable ceiling. Per-IP state table
              pre-allocated; eviction policy is operator-defined (evict-oldest / ban-all /
              drop-unbanned).
            </td>
            <td class="status"><span class="tag safe">Mitigated</span></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="tid">T.03</td>
            <td class="threat">Attacker triggers OOM to disable the banning daemon itself</td>
            <td class="mitig">
              Memory ceiling guarantee: fail2zig never exceeds the configured limit, regardless of
              input volume. Degraded-mode behavior is explicit, documented, and operator-selected.
            </td>
            <td class="status"><span class="tag safe">Mitigated</span></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="tid">T.04</td>
            <td class="threat">Supply-chain attack via a transitive dependency</td>
            <td class="mitig">
              Zero runtime dependencies. <code>zig build</code> from source. Reproducible builds. Binary
              checksums published with each release and signed with minisign + cosign.
            </td>
            <td class="status"><span class="tag safe">Mitigated</span></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="tid">T.05</td>
            <td class="threat">Attacker exploits fail2zig's own network listeners</td>
            <td class="mitig">
              The only optional listener is the Prometheus metrics endpoint &mdash; bind-restricted,
              read-only, no writable network surface in Phase 1. No socket protocol to attack.
            </td>
            <td class="status"><span class="tag safe">Mitigated</span></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="tid">T.06</td>
            <td class="threat">Privilege escalation via a daemon bug</td>
            <td class="mitig">
              Seccomp-BPF syscall filtering restricts the daemon to only syscalls it uses. Phase 2:
              full privilege-separation architecture with independent watcher / executor processes.
            </td>
            <td class="status"><span class="tag accent">Partial &middot; ph.2</span></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="tid">T.07</td>
            <td class="threat"
              >Log-injection via controlled service output (e.g. HTTP User-Agent)</td
            >
            <td class="mitig">
              Filters match on structural positions, not free-form substrings. Length limits and
              byte-class restrictions prevent crafted payloads from spanning fields.
            </td>
            <td class="status"><span class="tag safe">Mitigated</span></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="tid">T.08</td>
            <td class="threat">Malicious config file loaded from a writable path</td>
            <td class="mitig">
              Config paths default to <code>/etc/fail2zig/</code>; daemon refuses to start if config
              is world-writable. Import from fail2ban validates before applying.
            </td>
            <td class="status"><span class="tag safe">Mitigated</span></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="eyebrow"><span class="dot"></span>04 &middot; Audit &amp; disclosure</div>
        <div>
          <h2>What's been checked, by whom, and when.</h2>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <div class="audit-row">
          <div class="date">2026-04-10</div>
          <div class="title">
            Internal parser fuzz campaign &middot; 72h &middot; AFL++
            <p>
              Corpus of 4.1M lines across sshd, nginx, postfix filters. Zero crashes, zero hangs.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="status" style="color:var(--safe)">Passed</div>
        </div>
        <div class="audit-row">
          <div class="date">2026-03-28</div>
          <div class="title">
            Reproducible build verification &middot; Debian 12, Alpine 3.19, NixOS 24.05
            <p>Byte-identical output across all three environments. SBOM published.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="status" style="color:var(--safe)">Passed</div>
        </div>
        <div class="audit-row">
          <div class="date">2026-Q3 (planned)</div>
          <div class="title">
            External security audit &middot; pre-1.0 &middot; sponsor TBD
            <p>Scope: parser engine, allocator boundaries, privilege model, firewall backends.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="status" style="color:var(--accent)">Scheduled</div>
        </div>
        <div class="audit-row">
          <div class="date">&mdash;</div>
          <div class="title">
            Zero CVEs to date
            <p>
              Advisories will be published at{' '}
              <code>github.com/ul0gic/fail2zig/advisories</code> with 90-day embargo.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="status" style="color:var(--safe)">0 / 0</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap" style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:48px;align-items:start">
      <div>
        <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:16px"><span class="dot"></span>Reporting</div>
        <h2 style="font-size:28px;margin-bottom:12px">Responsible disclosure.</h2>
        <p class="lede" style="font-size:15px">
          File a report via{' '}
          <a
            href="https://github.com/ul0gic/fail2zig/issues/new?labels=security"
            style="color:var(--accent)"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"><strong>GitHub Issues</strong></a
          >
          with the <code>security</code> label. For embargoed disclosures, use GitHub's
          <a
            href="https://github.com/ul0gic/fail2zig/security/advisories/new"
            style="color:var(--accent)"
            rel="noopener noreferrer">private vulnerability reporting</a
          >.
        </p>
        <p style="color:var(--fg-dim);font-size:14px;margin-top:16px">
          We acknowledge within 48 hours. We ship a fix before disclosure, or coordinate a 90-day
          embargo with you directly. We don't run a bug bounty; we will credit you publicly unless
          you ask us not to.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="codeblock" style="padding:24px">
        <span class="cmt"># verify a release binary</span><br />
        <span class="prompt">$</span> minisign -V \<br />
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-P RWT<span style="color:var(--fg-mute)">&hellip;</span> \<br
        />
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-m fail2zig-x86_64-linux<br />
        <span class="muted">Signature and comment signature verified.</span><br />
        <br />
        <span class="cmt"># sbom</span><br />
        <span class="prompt">$</span> curl https://fail2zig.com/sbom/0.1.0.json<br />
        <br />
        <span class="cmt"># build from source (reproducible)</span><br />
        <span class="prompt">$</span> zig build -Doptimize=.ReleaseSafe \<br />
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-Dtarget=x86_64-linux-musl<br />
        <span class="muted">877 KB stripped</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page-header {
    padding: 64px 0 48px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
  }
  .page-header h1 {
    font-size: clamp(40px, 5vw, 64px);
    max-width: 22ch;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }
  .page-header .lede {
    font-size: 19px;
    max-width: 60ch;
  }
  .page-header .meta {
    display: flex;
    gap: 24px;
    margin-top: 32px;
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--fg-mute);
  }
  .page-header .meta span strong {
    color: var(--fg);
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .principles {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    border: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
  }
  .principle {
    padding: 32px;
    border-right: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
  }
  .principle:nth-child(2n) {
    border-right: none;
  }
  .principle:nth-last-child(-n + 2) {
    border-bottom: none;
  }
  .principle .idx {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    color: var(--accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .principle h3 {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 16px;
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .principle p {
    color: var(--fg-dim);
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0;
    max-width: 50ch;
  }

  .threat-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 14px;
    margin-top: 16px;
  }
  .threat-table th,
  .threat-table td {
    text-align: left;
    padding: 18px 20px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
    vertical-align: top;
  }
  .threat-table th {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--fg-mute);
    background: var(--bg-elev);
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  .threat-table tr:hover td {
    background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--bg-elev) 40%, transparent);
  }
  .threat-table .tid {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    color: var(--accent);
    width: 64px;
  }
  .threat-table .threat {
    color: var(--fg);
    max-width: 32ch;
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  .threat-table .mitig {
    color: var(--fg-dim);
    font-size: 13px;
    line-height: 1.55;
  }
  .threat-table .status {
    width: 140px;
  }

  .tcb-box {
    background: var(--bg-elev);
    border: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
    padding: 28px 32px;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 32px;
  }
  .tcb-col h4 {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--fg-mute);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    margin-bottom: 14px;
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  .tcb-col ul {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    list-style: none;
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 13px;
  }
  .tcb-col li {
    padding: 6px 0;
    color: var(--fg-dim);
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 10px;
  }
  .tcb-col li::before {
    content: '';
    width: 8px;
    height: 8px;
    display: inline-block;
  }
  .tcb-col.us li::before {
    background: var(--accent);
  }
  .tcb-col.them li::before {
    background: var(--fg-mute);
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .tcb-col .count {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 36px;
    color: var(--fg);
    font-weight: 500;
    margin-bottom: 4px;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
  }
  .tcb-col .count .unit {
    color: var(--fg-mute);
    font-size: 14px;
    margin-left: 6px;
  }

  .audit-row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 120px 1fr 120px;
    gap: 24px;
    padding: 20px 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
    align-items: center;
  }
  .audit-row:last-child {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
  }
  .audit-row .date {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--fg-mute);
  }
  .audit-row .title {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 14px;
    color: var(--fg);
  }
  .audit-row .title p {
    color: var(--fg-dim);
    font-family: var(--sans);
    font-size: 13px;
    margin: 4px 0 0;
  }
  .audit-row .status {
    text-align: right;
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  @media (max-width: 800px) {
    .principles,
    .tcb-box {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
    .principle {
      border-right: none !important;
    }
    .threat-table .status {
      display: none;
    }
    .audit-row {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 8px;
    }
  }
</style>
